    "narrative": "The Ghost Ride the WHIP lineup is well-positioned for today's slate, headlined by **Tyler Soderstrom** (76.91) and **Mickey Moniak** (75.75), who stand out as our most efficient starts. **Soderstrom** benefits from a soft matchup against Davis Martin and a significant park upgrade, while **Moniak** is a high-upside play against Tyler Glasnow; despite the daunting name on the mound, **Moniak**'s elite sprint speed and favorable platoon dynamics\u2014boosted by Glasnow\u2019s tendency to allow stolen base opportunities\u2014make him a mandatory start in our pursuit of category scarcity. **Austin Riley** (72.31) also projects as an elite play, as he capitalizes on a high-ceiling matchup against Taijuan Walker, where his strong plate discipline and lineup protection at the #4 spot outweigh the slight drag from the catcher\u2019s arm.\n\nWe are keeping a close eye on the weather in games involving **Vinnie Pasquantino**, **Giancarlo Stanton**, and **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, as the 31% rain risk introduces volatility to our most powerful bats. Notably, the optimizer favored the platoon-advantaged **Max Muncy** (61.91) and **Alex Freeland** (60.41) to round out the infield despite the latter hitting at the bottom of the order, largely because the matchup against Sugano offers a significant SP skill boost. **Trevor Story** came closest to cracking the starting nine with a 58.15 score, but was ultimately benched due to the lower efficiency ceiling compared to our high-sprint-speed outfield options and the defensive value of our current middle-infield configuration. \n\nManagers should note that the aggressive valuation of stolen bases keeps **Corbin Carroll** (63.48) locked in despite a tougher matchup against Braydon Fisher; the projected 85% SB success rate against this battery makes him a per-game anchor for our Roto standing. While **Luis Campusano** (43.96) holds the floor today, he remains the most vulnerable spot in the lineup given the tight platoon split against Jose Soriano. Monitor the weather reports closely, as any delay for **Vinnie Pasquantino** or **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** may necessitate a pivot to our deeper bench assets, though for now, the data supports sticking with the projected high-efficiency starters to maximize our daily cap utility.",
